INSERT INTO `comments` (`com_id`, `com_authorid`, `com_content`, `com_date`, `post_id`) VALUES
(5, 3, 'Have to say I find it amusing that despite brute-forcing it onto as many machines as possible, the red \'x\' fiasco, banning any other OS from getting updates on newer chips etc etc... they STILL had to exaggerate about how wonderful Windows 10 was doing. Lol', '2018-04-01 10:37:15', 31),
(6, 7, 'Yep. Microsoft once pushed out a dialog with the only two buttons being \"upgrade now\" and \"upgrade tonight\". The user needed to click the red X to make this go away, but it would come up over and over again because Microsoft strategically didn\'t provide a \"stop asking me\" button. And at the end of the campaign, Microsoft scheduled people into it anyway, so that the next time they clicked the red X like they grew accustomed to hundreds of times, they were actually \"agreeing\" to it.\r\n\r\nSome of us figured out that these nags were coming from a patch called KB3035583. The description of this in Windows Update read that it \"resolves issues in Windows\"; it said nothing about Windows 10. I suppose if Microsoft told us what it was actually going to do, more people would have avoided it. Anyway, for those of us who figured out the above and went and uninstalled KB3035583 while marking it as hidden to avoid it in the future, Microsoft overrode this and continuously installed it again anyway.', '2018-04-01 10:37:46', 31),
(7, 8, 'Why would anyone in their right mind try to put a 65W TDP budget-gaming CPU requiring active cooling and likely costing more than 3X the price of the 10W TDP Celeron in a fanless mini-PC primarily intended for large multi-unit classroom-type installations targeting less than 4.5W to 10W per unit power consumption?\r\nYou really should think these comments through before posting here.', '2018-04-01 14:50:50', 32),
(10, 9, 'Basically now the Intel Celeron is the cheapest processor that nobody wants anymore so that\'s what mintbox went with to keep costs low. Else the AMD 2200G would be a way better option for this form factor.', '2018-04-01 14:58:24', 32),
(11, 10, 'No real graphics performance.. that\'s garbage.. Give me a new AMD 12W AMD Ryzenâ„¢ Embedded V1000 processor.. 4C/8T \"Zen\" Cores 14nm, 3.6 FP16 TFLOPS, 4 Independent 4K Displays, and discrete GPU class performance APU..\r\n\r\nEverybody needs graphics for the operating system, to the windows management, to applications, to gaming.. Intel graphics are totally obsoleted..\r\n\r\nIntel is dead without high-end gpus.. Intel should put an AMD discreate gpu in their chips like they are doing on the other Intel chips..\r\n\r\nThe Ryzenâ„¢ Embedded V1000 processor is a monster for its size and capabilities..', '2018-04-01 14:59:58', 32),
(12, 10, 'Amazon exploits its employees to the fullest. Pays and pays them poverty wages...', '2018-04-01 15:02:37', 24),
(13, 10, 'Simply cuz they are using Windows.', '2018-04-01 15:03:13', 30),
(14, 10, 'But some of the usual suspects around here claim that nobody is worried about their privacy, spying is inevitable, everyone is doing it online and you may as well just \"give in\" to it or that an os or app can\'t get better or move forward without its creators spying on the user\'s.\r\n\r\nAnd then we see this extension for Firefox.', '2018-04-01 15:03:56', 28),
(15, 11, 'Bezos officially became the richest man in the world in late 2017, but this was the first year he bested Gates to get the No. 1 spot on Forbesâ€™ annual list of billionaires. Previously, Bezos was one of the top three richest people â€” coming in No. 3 in 2017 with a net worth of $72.8 billion. The Amazon founderâ€™s net worth climbed throughout the year thanks to growing Amazon share prices and key acquisitions at the company, including the purchase of Whole Foods for $13 billion in June 2017.', '2018-04-01 15:07:57', 24),
(16, 11, 'Hereâ€™s a quick test. With Mint 19 Cinnamon 64-bit, both the Pro and the Pro 2 run at roughly 37C at idle. We launch a youtube video in Firefox, a 1080p movie in MPV, a heavy PDF magazine in xreader, LO writer and the sysmonitor.\r\n\r\nThe Pro struggles a bit at the beginning (not very noticeable but you do see a few slow downs with the cursor while applications are being launched) and then itâ€™s smooth again. That use case settles at around 50% CPU usage on the 4 cores on avg and the temperature reaches 54C. It feels warm to the touch but not too hot..\r\n\r\nThe Pro2 doesnâ€™t show any signs of slow down when setting up the same apps/videos. The 4 cores reach an avg of about 40% usage and the temperature raises to about 40C. We can make it raise to 50C by moving the youtube/mpv videos around the screen and changing their sizes. The heatsink feels a little warm but not as much as with the Pro version.\r\n\r\nIâ€™m not sure this demonstrates anything. Thereâ€™s a visible difference in performance when launching the apps though and in how warm they feel when touching the heatsinks. Itâ€™s not night and day, but itâ€™s visible.', '2018-04-01 15:10:12', 32),
(17, 11, 'If the imbeciles at Microsoft would simply deign to substitute the public will for their own, they could have HAD a winner in Windows 10 long ago. \r\nIf they had realized that what they had said, indicated to many that Windows 10 would work one way on the desk and lap, and another in tablets and phones - and quit trying to force regression of the UI on the more powerful desk and lap version, people would have been far less testy.\r\nAllowing the far better looking interface of Vista and 7 with its shading and less clunky look would have meant far less griping. Aero was a zenith, and denying that shows tremendous stupidity.\r\nNo one denies the are things about Windows 10 which are better, but he basic UI is not one.', '2018-04-01 15:13:48', 31),
(18, 11, 'Just more confirmation of the horrible uptake of windows 10.\r\n\r\nWith project Polaris development currently concentrating on the migration aspects, windows subscription service being openly discussed, I give desktop windows less than two years and it\'s complete destruction will be complete.', '2018-04-01 15:22:20', 34),
(19, 12, 'You know software is in horrible shape and only getting worse when in 2018, a social media giant who is well known for their privacy invasions, are now doing more to try and satisfy the privacy concerns of their users than Microsoft is doing with windows 10.', '2018-04-01 15:25:51', 35),
(20, 12, 'Assuming MS is dumb enough to trash the Win32 application ecosystem then they deserve to lose market share. The problem MS is facing is partly a mature hardware market with the replacement cycle stretching out coupled with alternative devices that are better suited for some (rather large) niches. Also, Win32 applications are critical to businesses. Ditching the business market would suicide as it is a relatively stable, money maker. MS can survive rather nicely with businesses but will die if tries to be a consumer oriented company.', '2018-04-01 15:26:09', 34),
(21, 12, 'My parents are richer than Jeff Bezos!', '2018-04-01 15:26:36', 24),
(22, 13, 'Well, their acting like they care. I don\'t think any of us really believe it. The intelligence apparatuses of many governments have made full backdoor access a condition of FB operating within their borders. They did the same to Blackberry, who was far less willing to compromise and suffered for it greatly. I have no doubt that America\'s spook services have real-time, AI controlled monitoring of all major social networks. They have literally passed spending bills that include funding for it.', '2018-04-01 15:27:41', 35),
(23, 13, '\"Remember not until Windows 10 did MS purposely try to prevent end users from installing previous versions of Windows on newer hardware.\"\r\n\r\nYou can install any previous versions you like on newer hardware, no problem.\r\n\r\nWhat you will find though is either a) the hardware manufacturer will no longer be providing drivers, b) Microsoft won\'t be providing Windows Updates, or c) both of the above.\r\n\r\nIn other words, nothing different than what has happened over the past few decades, once operating systems become obsolete.', '2018-04-01 15:30:06', 34),
(24, 13, 'This Bezos guy shows up too much on the news. It\'s not like he is a Nobel laureate!', '2018-04-01 15:32:40', 24),
(25, 3, 'I disagree, FB is all talk.\r\nMS on the other hand, walking you through the process of privacy and settings, simplified their wording to make it easier to understand, the email you when term change, their apps work like iOS (if an app wants access to your camera or photos, it prompts you), and the next major update has the tools to see what is being sent back.', '2018-04-01 15:35:11', 35),
(26, 3, 'ughhh... what is this \'facebook\' thing?', '2018-04-01 18:21:02', 35),
(27, 3, 'I want to be a top commenter!!!', '2018-04-01 18:21:55', 35),
(28, 3, 'so i\'ll spam this post!', '2018-04-01 18:22:11', 35),
(29, 7, 'All spammers WILL be banned!', '2018-04-02 18:41:46', 35),
(30, 7, 'Sure, everybody needs graphics but not everybody needs discrete GPU class performance - particularly for the intended applications of these MintBox Minis (large multi-unit classroom and lab-type installations targeting less than 4.5W to 10W per unit power consumption) Intel graphics is more than sufficient for the majority of such applications.\r\n\r\nI\'ll agree the V1000 looks impressive... but I also wonder about the price for a product that was just announced vs the Celeron which has been in production for nearly 2 years.', '2018-04-05 18:19:35', 32),
(31, 3, 'SPAM!', '2018-04-05 19:36:03', 35);

